{{Islam by country}} [[File:Quba-Mosque Windhoek Namibia.jpg|thumb|''Quba Mosque'' in Windhoek]] '''Namibia''' is home to a small but growing Muslim community.
==Number of Muslims== While in 2009 insiders estimated the number of Muslims to be between 3,000 and 5,000 people,<ref name=IPS/> in 2011 it was estimated to be 9,000 Muslims,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pewforum.org/2011/01/27/table-muslim-population-by-country/|title=Table: Muslim Population by Country|publisher=Pew Research Center|date=27 January 2011|accessdate=13 March 2017}}</ref> many of whom are Nama.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://archive.islamonline.net/?p=18129|title=Islam in Namibia, making an impact|publisher=Islamonline.net}}</ref>
[[Islam]] along with [[Judaism]], [[Buddhism]], and the [[Baha'i Faith]], which make up the largest minority religions in [[Namibia]], but combined account for less than 1% of the population of Namibia.
==Growth of Namibia's Muslim community== Most of Namibia's Muslim community are members of the [[Nama people|Namaqua]] ethnic group.<ref name=IOL>[http://www.islamonline.net/English/News/2006-06/01/02.shtml IslamOnline.net- News<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> It is believed that this is mostly as a result of the efforts of a prominent politician among the Nama, [[Jacobs Salmaan Dhameer]], who converted to [[Islam]] in 1980.<ref name="IOL"/> The first [[mosque]] in the country, the ''Soweto Islamic Centre'', was established 1986 and is located in [[Katutura]]. As of May 2009, there were twelve mosques in the country, six in [[Windhoek]], two in [[Katima Mulilo]], one in [[Walvis Bay]], and three in the north of the country in the former [[Ovamboland]].<ref name=IPS>Nathalie Rosa Bucher (12 May 2009): [http://www.ipsnews.net/2009/05/religion-namibia-finding-sanctuary-in-islam/ Finding Sanctuary in Islam] ''[[Inter Press Service News Agency]]''</ref>
The ''Namibia Islamic Judicial Council'' is based on [[Ondobe]] in the [[Ohangwena Region]].<ref>[http://www.ijcnam.org ijcnam.org]</ref> NIHA (Namibia Islamic Halaal Association) is Namibia's oldest and most well known Halaal Certifying body, recognised by the Halaal Certification body in South Africa and in many Islamic states. NIHA was established in 2001 and before known as the ''Namibia Halaal Slaughterers Association''. It certifies food outlets in the country.
