{{Infobox religious building | name = {{nihongo|Nanyo Shrine|南洋神社}} | image = Nanyo Shrine.JPG | caption = Nanyo Shrine at Koror – ''circa'' 1940 | map_type = Palau | map_alt = | coordinates = | map_relief = | map_size = | map_caption = | religious_affiliation = [[Shinto]] | type = ''Kanpei-taisha'' | deity = [[Amaterasu]] | founded_by = | established = 1–3 November 1940 | date_destroyed = 1944 | location = [[Koror]], [[Palau]] | website = | architecture_style = | festival = | leadership = }}
{{nihongo|'''Nanyo Shrine'''|南洋神社|Nan'yō-jinja}} is a [[Shinto]] shrine located on the island of [[Koror]], in [[Palau]]. The shrine was the ''ichinomiya'' of the government of the [[South Pacific Mandate]], a [[League of Nations mandate]]d territory administered by the [[Empire of Japan]]. It was established in 1940 and designated for the veneration of [[Amaterasu Omikami]].<ref name="peattie226">Peattie, Mark R. (1988). [https://books.google.com/books?id=DHxdSkoo4AMC&pg=PA226&dq= ''Nanʻyō: the rise and fall of the Japanese in Micronesia, 1885–1945,'' p. 226.]</ref>
==History== The process which led to the establishment of the shrine began mid-1930s when the regional planning agency (''Nan'yō Takushoku'') was charged with the Japanization of [[Micronesia]].<ref>Guichard-Anguis, Sylvie ''et al.'' (2009). [https://books.google.com/books?id=3yTBsgZcsD8C&pg=PA181&dq= ''Japanese Tourism and Travel Culture,'' p. 181.]</ref> The chief advocate for the shrine was Domoto Teiichi, who had been the Private Secretary to the [[Governor of the South Pacific Mandate]] since 1936.<ref name="peattie226"/>
The enshrinement ceremonies took three days, November 1–3, 1940 (''[[Showa Era|Showa]] 15, 1st–3rd day of the 11th month'')<!-- NengoCalc: 昭和十五年十一月一日 -->. The shrine was situated at Koror because it was the Japanese colonial capital. From the outset, the Nan'yō Shrine was officially designated one of the ''Kanpei-taisha'' (官幣大社), meaning that it stood in the first rank of government-supported shrines.<ref>Peattie, [https://books.google.com/books?id=DHxdSkoo4AMC&pg=PA225&dq= pp. 225–229.]</ref> The shrine was construed by the Japanese government as marking "a step forward in the sacred task of constructing a New East Asian Order."<ref>Peattie, [https://books.google.com/books?id=DHxdSkoo4AMC&pg=PA229&dq= p. 229.]</ref>
When the [[Allies of World War II|Allied]] forces threatened Palau in late 1944, the ''[[kami]]'' and sacred symbols of the shrine were evacuated to Japan by submarine. The shrine remained untouched by American bombing; but Japan's defeat in [[World War II]] ended this colonial administration and a sense of reverence for the shrine structures which were dismantled for use in rebuilding Koror. Only the stone steps to the upper platform and the great stone lanterns still remain as evidence of the former shrine precincts.<ref name="peattie339">Peattie, [https://books.google.com/books?id=DHxdSkoo4AMC&pg=PA339&dq= p. 339 n61.]</ref>
In 1983, plans were developed for a reconstruction of the shrine at its former site,<ref name="peattie339"/> and a miniature replica of the original shrine was completed with the funding of private sponsors from [[Japan]] in 1993.<ref>[http://www.asahi-net.or.jp/~un3k-mn/0815-hisaizu.htm 南洋神社], [[Asahi Shimbun]], September 21, 2009</ref>
